04405nam a22006975i 9781400826728DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20092005nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97814008267287 a10.1515/97814008267282doi  a(DE-B1597)453549  a(OCoLC)979744899  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aHV8698 .S273 2007 7aLAW0520002bisacsh04a345.7731 aSarat, Austin, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMercy on Trial :bWhat It Means to Stop an Execution /cAustin Sarat.  aCourse Book 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2009] 4c©2005  a1 online resource (352 p.) :b2 tables.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tChapter 1. Mercy, Clemency, and Capital Punishment The Illinois Story -- tChapter 2. Capital Clemency in the Twentieth Century -- tChapter 3. The Jurisprudence of Clemency -- tChapter 4. Governing Clemency From Redemption to Retribution -- tChapter 5. Clemency without Mercy -- tChapter 6. Conclusion -- tAppendix A. George Ryan: -- tAppendix B. Capital Clemency, 1900–2004 -- tAppendix C. Chronology of Capital Clemency, 1900–2004 -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aOn January 11, 2003, Illinois Governor George Ryan--a Republican on record as saying that "some crimes are so horrendous . . . that society has a right to demand the ultimate penalty"--commuted the capital sentences of all 167 prisoners on his state's death row. Critics demonized Ryan. For opponents of capital punishment, however, Ryan became an instant hero whose decision was seen as a signal moment in the "new abolitionist" politics to end killing by the state. In this compelling and timely work, Austin Sarat provides the first book-length work on executive clemency. He turns our focus from questions of guilt and innocence to the very meaning of mercy. Starting from Ryan's controversial decision, Mercy on Trial uses the lens of executive clemency in capital cases to discuss the fraught condition of mercy in American political life. Most pointedly, Sarat argues that mercy itself is on trial. Although it has always had a problematic position as a form of "lawful lawlessness," it has come under much more intense popular pressure and criticism in recent decades. This has yielded a radical decline in the use of the power of chief executives to stop executions. From the history of capital clemency in the twentieth century to surrounding legal controversies and philosophical debates about when (if ever) mercy should be extended, Sarat examines the issue comprehensively. In the end, he acknowledges the risks associated with mercy--but, he argues, those risks are worth taking.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 7aLAW / Jurisprudence.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044250240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978140082672840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781400826728423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781400826728.jpg  a978-3-11-044250-2  Princeton University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LAEC  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LAEC  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK